<author><name><![CDATA[psycopathicteen]]></name></author>
<updated>2010-09-21T17:42:51-07:00</updated>
<published>2010-09-21T17:42:51-07:00</published>
<id>http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=6913&amp;p=67731#p67731</id>
<link href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=6913&amp;p=67731#p67731"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[Project SNES: character design, powerups, levels etc]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=6913&amp;p=67731#p67731"><![CDATA[
I'm now using a modified version of my old dynamic animation engine.<br /><br />My old engine uploaded 64 16x16 sprite cells over 2 consecutive frames (32 cells each) with the other 64 sprites using permanant v-ram sprite patterns.<br /><br />My new engine is a little bit simpler.  It uploads 96 16x16 sprite cells over 2 consecutive frames (48 cells each) without using any permanant v-ram sprite patterns.<br /><br />But they both rely on the same double buffer, 1-frame-oam-delay method that I came up with.  Both versions have advantages and disadvantages, but the second method doesn't take as much thinking when you want to add in a new character or object.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=4383">psycopathicteen</a> — Tue Sep 21, 2010 5:42 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
